# Auto-push docs/ and mockups/

The repo serves a public site from `docs/` via GitHub Pages
(`demo.regionallyfamous.com`). The concept queue at
`docs/concepts/index.html` is regenerated from `mockups/*.png` by
`bin/build-redirects.py`. Both surfaces are meant to track HEAD
continuously so the public-facing bench always reflects what the agent
just produced.

## The standing rule

**Whenever the working tree has uncommitted changes under `docs/` or
`mockups/`, commit and push them at the end of the turn that produced
them. Do not ask the Proprietor first.** This includes:

- New `mockups/mockup-<slug>.png` files (fresh concept cards)
- Modified `mockups/mockup-<slug>.png` files (refreshed cards)
- Any regeneration of `docs/` (concept queue, redirect pages, mockup
  copies, snap gallery, `docs/index.html`)
- New themes shipped under `docs/<slug>/` plus their mockup card moving
  from "queued" to "shipped"

## How to do it

1. If you generated mockups but didn't yet rebuild the queue, run
   `python3 bin/build-redirects.py` first so `docs/concepts/index.html`
   and `docs/mockups/<slug>.png` pick up the changes.
2. Stage everything under `docs/` and `mockups/`:
   ```bash
   git add docs/ mockups/
   ```
3. Commit with a message that names what changed (concept slugs added,
   refreshed, or shipped). Group related changes in one commit:
   ```bash
   git commit -m "$(cat <<'EOF'
   Add Ember, Foundry, Holler concepts; refresh Klang, Cog, Pulp mockups

   New tiny/small/medium-tier concept cards painted and queued.
   docs/concepts/index.html now reads 27 in queue, 1 shipped.
   EOF
   )"
   ```
4. Push to `main`:
   ```bash
   git push
   ```
5. The pre-commit and pre-push hooks (`bin/check.py --visual`) run as
   normal. **If a hook fails on files you actually touched, fix the
   failure and re-commit.** If the hook fails entirely on territory
   outside the staged change set (a theme you didn't touch is red at
   HEAD because of a previous agent's drift), use `--no-verify` so the
   docs/mockups push lands, and:
   - name the bypassed checks in the commit message body
   - in the same turn, surface the unrelated failure to the Proprietor
     in chat so they can decide whether to fix it now or queue it
   This keeps the public queue moving without absorbing other agents'
   regressions, and never silently hides a check.

   ### Bypass blocklist — checks `--no-verify` MUST NOT skip

   Some failures mean **shipped markup is broken on the live demo**, not
   just "stale CI gate". For these, `--no-verify` is forbidden — fix the
   underlying theme first, even if the docs push has to wait a turn:

   - **`Block markup matches save() output`** (the static heading-typography
     /group-class /accordion-role /button-type invariants in `bin/check.py`).
     A failure here means a `wp:heading` or `wp:group` block has JSON
     attributes that don't match its rendered markup. The editor's
     deprecation pipeline silently rewrites the markup at editor-load,
     but the FRONT-END serves the bare markup, so the production demo
     renders the wrong thing. Past incident: aero/lysholm/selvedge
     footer column titles shipped as 4-7.5rem display headings instead
     of 15px uppercase labels because three `wp:heading` blocks had
     `fontSize:"sm"` + `style.typography.*` JSON but bare `<h2>` markup.
     `--no-verify` shipped that to production for weeks.
   - **`Block markup passes the @wordpress/blocks editor-parity validator`**
     (the Node validator in `bin/blocks-validator/`). A "silent
     deprecation" failure here means the same class of bug — the editor
     is auto-upgrading legacy markup on load. The static check above
     catches the most common shape (heading typography); this one is
     the catch-all for everything else. Treat it the same way.

   Before bypassing the hook, inspect the failure list. If any failure
   is on one of these checks, FIX IT FIRST regardless of which staged
   files you "own". The cost of a wrong-render shipping to the demo
   site dwarfs the cost of a one-turn delay on the docs push.

## What this rule does NOT cover

- **Theme code changes** (`<slug>/templates/`, `<slug>/parts/`,
  `<slug>/theme.json`, etc.) — those follow the normal "only commit
  when explicitly requested" rule from the system prompt.
- **`tmp/`, scratch files, baselines under
  `tests/visual-baseline/`** — those need explicit permission per the
  usual rules.
- **Force-pushes, amends, or anything destructive** — the safety
  protocol from the system prompt still applies. Auto-push means
  fast-forward `git push` only.

If a `docs/` change is mixed into a commit that *also* touches theme
code or unreviewed scratch, split the commit so the `docs/` portion
ships under this rule and the theme portion waits for the Proprietor's
nod.

## Rationale

The concepts queue is the marketing surface of the project — it's how
prospective Proprietors and casual visitors see what's on the bench.
Letting fresh concept cards sit uncommitted on a single workstation
defeats the whole point of a public queue. The Proprietor has standing
authorisation: paint a card, push the card.
